title: Tour de Ranch Dirty Fondo
description: Hammer Down Multisport is proud to present the 17th Annual Tour de Ranch Gran Fondo and the ALL NEW Dirty Fondo thru the rolling hills of beautiful Northwest Florida. The Tour de Ranch is an excellent early season fitness tests for Mt Bikers and Road Racers. If you like quiet rolling county dirt roads with a few climbs to stretch out your legs and put the hammer down this ride is for you!
course:
Local cycling icons, Paul Brannon and Bob McDonald discovered portions of this route during the 2012 Tour de Ranch. Never the conformists, Paul and Bob were looking to do an epic endurance mountain bike route that traversed the similar terrain as the Tour de Ranch…but only on dirt. This dirt route leverages the same start, finish and rest stops as the other Tour de Ranch Fondo routes, so you will still be part of the grand event. In fact, we anticipate many of the DirtyFondo riders will be trying to beat their buddies doing the GranFondo to the after ride BBQ!

This route is not for sissies. The roads are the best representation of old Florida Country dirt roads such as the challenging Hard Labor Road and the finishing stretch of rolling hills on Ebenezer Road. Traversing over 48 miles of back country dirt roads, this is one route that you will truly enjoy. Just under 900ft of elevation gain, these rolling country roads will sap the energy out of even the most seasoned endurance mt. biker. If you have not gone Dirty…this may be the route to switch you over
registration: Register through Active.com
notes: Awards will be given for the GranFondo King and  Queen of Strava Segment, Overall King and Queen of the GranFondo, and Overall King and Queen of the Dirty Fondo

title: Delray Beach Twilight Festival Amateur Races
Fort DeSoto Time Trial Series
description: Classes: Men, Women, Merckx, Juniors, Handcycle, Fixed Gear. Juniors under 18 are required to have parent or guardian sign entry and release forms. Cash payout for individual races 1st thru 3rd – Overall Men, Women, Fixies, and Merckx. $20/15/10 ( That\'s $1440 over eight races!). No riders under 10 years of age allowed. No recumbents per USA Cycling rules. Series categories: Men 19-29, 30-39, 40-49, 50-59, 60+ , Merckx, Fixed, Junior, Handcycle, and Women 19-44, 45+. Categories with less than three riders will be combined. Five out of the eight races count toward the overall series points race. Four races needed to qualify. Medals and prizes for series winners 1st thru 3rd places in each group. Start: The event starts promptly at 6:30 pm. Cyclists start at 30 second intervals. Start times are posted online by 4:00 pm day of event. Start times are seeded based on previous times.
course: Fort Desoto is as flat as it gets. All cyclists do an out and back from the very end of the North beach to complete a distance of 15 Kilometers.
registration:
Online at www.fortdesototimetrial.com, maximum 50 racers. Registration opens one week prior to each race at 7PM. Entry of $15 ($5 Junior entry)can be paid on site, but NO on-site registration will be available. 
email Ted at \"info@fortdesototimetrial.com\" to get on the mailing list.
notes: Merckx Class definition: NO aero gear at all. That includes booties, aero helmets, deep rims (34mm bead to edge max), tt frames, tt bars, etc. - Skinsuits are OK. Violators will be relegated to respective age class.
directions: Fort Desoto Park in Pinellas County, FL. Follow I-275 South to Pinellas Bayway> Fort Desoto Park> North Beach.

title: Gulf Coast Interstate Relay
description: The Gulf Coast Interstate (GCI) Relay, an innovative cycling relay event will take place April 4-6, 2013.  Cycling teams will complete 263 miles from New Orleans, Louisiana to Pensacola Beach, Florida.
course: The GCI Relay start is in New Orleans, Louisiana, Lakefront at the UNO Research and Technology Park. The relay finish is in Pensacola Beach, Florida, Oceanfront on Casino Beach Road by The Pavilion. In between: mostly Lake bridges and swampland in Louisiana, beachfront through Mississippi (Gulfport, Biloxi, Pascagoula), mostly wide-open country roads through Alabama, except for the trek through the City of Mobile and over the Cochrane Bridge, 15 miles of country rode in Florida, through downtown Pensacola for a finish on Pensacola Beach.
